**Useful output power of the solar–cell**

Let  

* \(A\) – collector (cell) area  
* \(R_{\odot}\) – solar radius  
* \(d_{\odot}\) – distance to the Sun  
* \(T_{s}\) – solar effective temperature  
* \(E_{g}=h\,\nu _{g}=k_{B}T_{s}\,x_{g}\) – band‑gap energy  

The radiation left at the cell is the black‑body spectrum of the Sun divided by the geometrical factor \(\pi R_{\odot}^{2}/d_{\odot}^{2}\).  
The spectral photon flux (photons s\(^{-1}\) m\(^{-2}\) Hz\(^{-1}\)) emitted by a black body is  

\[
\phi_{\nu}=\frac{2\pi\nu^{2}}{c^{2}}\,
\frac{1}{\exp\!\left(\tfrac{h\nu}{k_{B}T_{s}}\right)-1}\; .
\]

Only photons with energy \(h\,\nu\ge E_{g}\) can be harvested.  
The useful optical power collected by the cell is therefore

\[
P_{\rm out}=A\;\frac{\pi R_{\odot}^{2}}{d_{\odot}^{2}}\;
\int_{\nu_{g}}^{\infty}\!h\nu\;\phi_{\nu}\;d\nu ,
\qquad \nu_{g}\equiv \frac{E_{g}}{h}=\frac{k_{B}T_{s}}{h}\,x_{g}.
\]

Insert the expression for \(\phi_{\nu}\) and change the integration variable from
\(\nu\) to \(x=h\nu/(k_{B}T_{s})\):

\[
\begin{aligned}
P_{\rm out}
&=A\,\frac{\pi R_{\odot}^{2}}{d_{\odot}^{2}}\;
\frac{2\pi}{c^{2}}
\!\int_{x_{g}}^{\infty}\! 
\frac{(k_{B}T_{s})^{3}}{h^{3}}\;
\frac{h\,x\,(k_{B}T_{s})/h}
{\exp(x)-1}\;dx\\[4pt]
&=A\,\frac{2\pi^{2}R_{\odot}^{2}}{c^{2}\,d_{\odot}^{2}}
\left(\frac{k_{B}T_{s}}{h}\right)^{3}k_{B}T_{s}\;
\int_{x_{g}}^{\infty}\!
\frac{x^{3}}{e^{x}-1}\;dx .
\end{aligned}
\]

Collecting the constants gives the compact form

\[
\boxed{\;P_{\rm out}
=A\,\frac{2\pi^{2}R_{\odot}^{2}}{c^{2}d_{\odot}^{2}}
\left(\frac{k_{B}T_{s}}{h}\right)^{4}
\int_{x_{g}}^{\infty}\!\frac{x^{3}}{e^{x}-1}\;dx\;}
\]

or, equivalently,  

\[
P_{\rm out}=A\,\frac{\pi R_{\odot}^{2}}{d_{\odot}^{2}}\;
\sigma T_{s}^{4}\;
\frac{2}{\pi^{4}}\,
\int_{x_{g}}^{\infty}\!\frac{x^{3}}{e^{x}-1}\;dx ,
\]

where \(\sigma=\pi^{2}k_{B}^{4}/(60\hbar^{3}c^{2})\) is the Stefan–Boltzmann constant.
This expression gives the useful optical power that the cell can harvest in terms of the dimensionless band‑gap parameter \(x_{g}\), the collector area \(A\), the solar radius \(R_{\odot}\), the Sun–cell distance \(d_{\odot}\), the solar temperature \(T_{s}\), and the fundamental constants \(c\), \(h\) and \(k_{B}\).

